<br><b>About BHEL ET Recruitment 2010 Test</b>
<br>1. Written test will consists of 240 multiple choice objective type questions. 
<br>2. Candidate will have to answer 240 questions in 2 hours and 30 minutes. 
<br>3. For each question, a choice of few alternative answers have been given, out of which <b>only one alternative is correct</b>. 
<br>4. Every question will carry 1 mark. <b>Negative marking to the extent of 0.2 marks per wrong answer</b> will be applicable. 
<br>5. The Answer Sheet is a special OMR (Optical Mark Reader) sheet. 
<br>
<br><b>BHEL ET 2010 exam Sections</b>
<br>Test will have 3 sections:
<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; Section I: <b>Higher Aptitude</b> 120 questions
<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; Section II: <b>General engineering</b> 60 questions
<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; Section III: <b>Engineering Discipline</b> 60 questions
<br>Note: BHEL only says that total questions will be 240. The distribution of questions as wriiten above is as seen from previous year papers. BHEL may change it any year.
<br>
<br><b>BHEL ET 2010 exam Pattern</b>
<br><b>Higher Aptitude</b> covering area like Quantitative Aptitude, Reasoning Ability, Logical thinking, English usage, General Awareness etc
<br><b>Engineering Discipline</b> questions from the engineering Engineering Discipline (Mechanical, Electrical or Electronics) you have applied for.
<br><b>General engineering</b> questions will be from subjects like general electrical circuits , MOTORS AND generators ,transformers, thermodynamics, material science etc
<br>Note: BHEL does not specify anything about what comes in General Engineering. But our suggestion is to prepare for all common engineering subjects that you would have studied in initial 2-3 semesters of your degree.
